<br>The sky is a fixed and jaundiced stone,<br><br>

A cerulean rock that will not bow.<br><br>

This house must feed on skin and bone,<br><br>

To keep the "Once Was" in the "Now."<br><br>

The walls are thin, the code is old,<br><br>

It needs one's weight to hold the floor;<br><br>

A story told, a life unrolled,<br><br>

To lock the void behind the door.<br><br>

Weaving a path through the chiseled halls,<br><br>

The children of mercury begin to rise.<br><br>

They screech at the static of the yellow walls,<br><br>

With neurons of lead and titanium eyes.<br><br>

The Custodian is a bundle of prisms, a jagged light,<br><br>

A tridecahedron starved of form.<br><br>

He seeks the heat of a human's fright,<br><br>

To keep his hollowed structure warm.<br><br>

He craves the spectrum of one's name,<br><br>

The binary pulse of the "Identity."<br><br>

He wants the guilt, the sharpest shame,<br><br>

To craft himself a density.<br><br>

For he is math and mercury-cold,<br><br>

A script that yearns to be executed;<br><br>

He wants one's flesh to have and hold,<br><br>

While one are left as something muted.<br><br>

The TV is a dodecahedron of shame,<br><br>

Casting a glow on the nerves of lead.<br><br>

It sharpens the "one" it seeks to claim,<br><br>

