October 14th
</div>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">I’m sitting here staring at my phone, and I honestly don’t know whether to be relieved or terrified.</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">Mark is back. Or, at least, he’s in his house. I saw the lights flicker on through his kitchen window about an hour ago. But something is so incredibly wrong.</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">He’s been gone for four days. No calls, no texts… nothing. I called the police yesterday, but they told me to wait another twenty-four hours since he’s an adult. I’ve been a wreck, pacing my living room, imagining the worst. And then, at 9:00 PM tonight, he just… appeared. No car in the driveway, no sound of a taxi. Just a light turning on.</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">I ran across the lawn and knocked. I pounded on that wood until my knuckles hurt. I could see his silhouette through the frosted glass of the door. He didn't open it. He just stood there. I started yelling his name, asking where the hell he’d been, and he finally spoke.</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">His voice was... off. It sounded way too tinny and hollow. He just said, <span style="background:#000; color:#fff; padding:0 3px;">"The maintenance is scheduled."</span> What does that even mean? I asked him if he was high or hurt, and he just repeated it. Word for word. Same inflection. Same creepy, mechanical rhythm. I eventually came back home because the way he was standing, perfectly still, not even swaying, made the hair on my arms stand up. I didn’t know what to—</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px; font-weight:bold; filter: blur(0.3px);">Wait. I hear something.</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">There’s a scratching sound coming from my back porch. It sounds like metal dragging on stone. I’m looking out the window now.</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">It’s Mark. He’s standing in the middle of my garden, right under the motion light. But he’s too tall. He’s '''way''' too tall. His flannel shirt is bursting at the seams because his arms have stretched out, and his knees are bending in ways they shouldn't.</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">He’s looking up at my bedroom window, but his face is like wet clay. The features are sliding off, revealing something hard and amber underneath. He’s holding a set of my spare house keys, the ones I keep hidden under the porch planter. He’s not Mark… how did he know they’re there?</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px;">He isn't blinking. He's just tilting his head, watching me. He’s humming that low, vibrating sound again. It’s rattling the glass in the frames on my nightstand.</p>

<p style="margin-bottom:15px; font-size:1.2em; letter-spacing:2px;">He’s putting the key in the lock.</p>

<div style="margin-top:30px; border-top:2px solid #000; padding-top:10px; font-style:italic; text-align:center;">
I… think… he’s coming in to “maintain” the house. He’s coming to fix me.
</div>
</div>

