<p>I thought The Custodian was hunting me. I thought the heavy, wet footsteps in the attic were a countdown to my own erasure. But I found him today. I found where he goes when the house stops humming.</p>

<p>He was in the living room. I stayed outside for approximately 600 minutes, and the sky turned off. The wallpaper there is peeling in the shape of my house. He wasn't standing. He wasn't sanding the walls or painting over my memories. He was just... sitting.</p>

<p>He sat on a sofa that smelled like old dust and forgotten winters, far too familiar. His impossibly long limbs folded like a broken umbrella. He didn't turn his clay face toward me. He didn't even twitch when the floorboards creaked under my weight. He was staring at the TV.</p>

<p>The screen didn't show static. It showed a backyard. A birthday party from 1994. I saw a little girl blowing out candles, and I realised... that’s the memory I dug up in the field three days ago. It wasn't mine. It must have been mine. Or it was the house’s. He was watching the memory I had stolen, and for the first time, he looked small.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 25px; font-style: italic; border-left: 3px solid #c4bca3; padding-left: 15px;">Observation #09:</p> 
<p>The TV cycled through images. A graduation. A car crash. A quiet breakfast. Every time a new scene appeared, the Custodian’s fingers would twitch, almost tracing the edges of the screen as if trying to feel the heat of the sun through the glass.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 25px; font-style: italic; border-left: 3px solid #c4bca3; padding-left: 15px;">Observation #10:</p> 
<p>I left a memory splinter on the coffee table. A small one... the feeling of holding someone’s hand in a crowded theatre. I watched from the doorway. He picked it up with those wet, grey fingers. He didn't absorb it. He just held it against the screen and hummed a melody that sounded like a lullaby played through a radiator.</p>

<p>He’s still there. He’s been watching for hours. I think he’s waiting for me to finish digging up the rest of the floorboards. He doesn't want to stop me. He wants more channels to watch. He wants to remember who he was before Once Was claimed his face.</p>

<p>I’m going back to the kitchen. There’s a loose board under the sink that feels like a summer rainstorm. I think I’ll give that one to him, too. We’re both just audience members now.</p>

